sacerdotes nominare. The priests referred to are the augurs. In chublican times the election to this priesthood was by cooptatio, but afterwards the appointment lay in the hands of the emperor. The College of Augurs seems, how- ever, to have preserved the privilege of nominatio by which they could indicate the person whom they deemed worthy of election. Pliny, as we see here, was repeatedly nominated by Verginius, and from iv. 8, 3 we learn that he was subse- quently nominated by Julius Frontinus, whom he at last succeeded, for several consecutive years before he obtained the pricsthood.
